		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    A Complete Guide to Killing Gnomes</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:pants_mechanic@yahoo.com">Kaiyan- Monk of Tallon Zek</a> | 
		            8/17/2001 6:12:49 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">INTRODUCTION:<BR>
<BR>
Gnomes: a race of plaguebringers known through out most of Norrath for their odd trinkets and inventions.  They live mostly in seclusion, preferring to work on their magics and inventions rather than socialize...  growing paler and physicaly weaker in their suburban necropolis known as Ak'anon.<BR>
Most people think of Gnomes as cute little short people who have funny noses and unusually wrinkled faces, but the truth is far worse.  <BR>
So, you may ask, what could be wrong about a race of such people?  Quite simply, my friend, they are fun to kill.  The joy in watching their tiny, frail bodies drop to the floor with a soft thud after being smashed by a well-placed War Hammer strike to the head or combination of deadly spells is overwhelming.<BR>
The best part is that EVERYBODY can take part in this fun and increasingly popular activity (so long as its on a PVP server).  You needn't be scared or shy because I present to you: A Complete Guide to Killing Gnomes.<BR>
IMPORTANT: Parts I and II are optional reading for the more serious hunter.  To simply jump right in and start the butchering, simply read Part III.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
PART I: THE GNOME AT HOME:<BR>
<BR>
Before we begin on how to actually kill the Gnome, let us study him in his own, and foreign, habitats.  I began my research with a Gnome known as Namfoodle, a wizard of sorts living in his home-town of Ak'anon.  Know Namfoodle, or Nam Nam as his friends called him, grew up in a very sheltered environment.  After years of research though and getting wrinkles, he felt that he was ready to begin adventuring.  From my hidden research station atop a large mountain near Ak'anon (a place on a hill where I sat), I viewed the young Wizard's progression.  He began by continuously killing large insects and other small bipedal creatures.  For many a moon Namfoodle killed these creatures (expected levels 1 to 5).  He only conversed with several other Gnomes during this time, and whenever he talked he just repeated some part of what the other Gnome had said in a question; something about telescopes I beleive.  <BR>
This part of my research was very important, for I got to study the Gnome (or Gnomicus Midgotus) out of actual combat, to see how they acted.  <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
PART II: THE GNOME IN FOREIGN CULTURES:<BR>
<BR>
One fateful day, as I prepared for another session of viewing Namfoodle kill unintelligent animals, the young Gnome put off hunting this day and began travelling.  He began walking North, and I recorded a very important conversation; Namfoodle's first interaction with another species.  Unfortunately, it was not so special because the other person was a mountain Dwarf, distant cousin to the Gnome, so I could expect no misunderstandings or arguments.  Namfoodle seemed amazed by the Dwarf's dazzling plate mail armor and his fine, magical sword and shield.  The two seemed to be heading in the same direction, so they accompanied each other.  <BR>
Soon, Namfoodle and his Dwarven friend began entering an area filled with great trees; a lively forest where all the animals roamed and birds chirped in their oak sanctuaries (trees).  This area is known as the Greater Faydark. <BR>
It is hear that I document a great interaction between the Gnome and another race.  Three Elven males approach Namfoodle and his friend.  Each pair constantly cons (considers) each other, but Namfoodle knows he is safe for he is out of level range for combat with other players.  After much conning, one of the High Elfs says,  <BR>
&quot;D00d, u r a dick.&quot;  After this the three Elves assault and kill the Dwarf, calling Nam Nam a &quot;n00b&quot; before running away.  <BR>
This left Namfoodle very confused and angered at the Elves.  &quot;Why had they done such a thing?&quot; he asks himself.  I want to explain it to the young Wizard but I know that interaction with hi would ruin my project, so I stay safe behind, the only cover my cunning, cat-like skill and the great trees.  <BR>
I soon learned after two days of viewing that Namfoodle's only reason for travelling was to hunt even more beasts, this time the endless hordes of Orcs, enemy to the fair Elven folk.  Fortunately (for himself), Namfoodle has had no interaction with another race during his time hunting.  Namfoodle grows in power, and soon begins hunting in the lair of Clan Crushbone, a place which will be his death...<BR>
On his first trip to Crushbone, The Gnome encounters 2 Elves, signifigantly lower in level than him.  Feeling cruel and wanting vengence for his Dwarven friend days ago, he decides to attack and slay these two Elves, not noting their guild tags.  After quite easily using his awesome magics to destroy the two elves, he ventures into Clan Crushbone to begin hunting, a smile on his demented, wrinkled lips.  I find it even more difficult to keep appropriate cover in such a place, so I pretend to be hunting the weakling Orcs here as well, quietly trailing Namfoodle and his actions.<BR>
Suddenly though, Namfoodle becomes suspicious of me.  He turns around and questions me threateningly.  If I wanted I could easily slay the little Gnome but that would ruin weeks of research!  Before we are about to enter mortal combat, several Humans and Elves approach us.  They are from the same guild of the two Elves Namfoodle had killed earlier, and now they were ready for payback.  They easily slaughter the poor Gnome, and I can't help but have a tear in my eye as Namfoodle looks past the whirling blades and bludgeoning maces to me, a confused look on his face.<BR>
Thus, the subject dead, I feel that I have enough material neccesary to begin putting facts the test, and start hunting Gnomes.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
PART III: HUNTING AND KILLING A GNOME           <BR>
<BR>
OK, so now you are ready to actually hunt and kill the Gnome.  You have made a wise decision, my friend.  <BR>
There are several ways in which to go about hunting the Gnome, I will describe a few, now.<BR>
I have done massive research on the Gnome and can say from experience and a watchful eye that Gnomes LOVE gadgets.  Anything they can get their hands on; trinkets, buttons, tools, all of the such they love.  You can use this to your advantage.  Simply place a small gadget or knick-knack under a large box.  Prop the box up against a stick, a rope tied to the stick being held by you or your partner, ready for tugging.  You should place it in an area where Gnomes frequent.  As soon as a Gnome comes by and goes to grab the gadget, YOINK!  Pull the string and you have yourself a Gnome!<BR>
Use your imagination to come up with other ways to use gadgets as Gnome bait!  Be fun and inventive!<BR>
Another way in which my partners and I captured several Gnomes was using disguises.  Throughout the Gnome cities are sentries placed here and there known as Watchers.  They act as guards and can give useful information.  Simply have you and your comrades dress up as these robotic helpers and wait for an unsuspecting Gnome to come by and ask for information.  When he does so, GRAB HIM!  Be warned though, it is wise to do so with more than one person because Gnomes are known to travel in groups of up to 6.<BR>
The easiest way to capture the Gnome is if you are in an area with very few Gnomes, such as the Human cities.  If you and your companions are together and you see a Gnome pass by in an area not frequented by Gnomes often, then take the oppurtunity and GRAB HIM!  Use your sheer numbers to overwhelm the little bastard, and luckily he won't even have a chane to get a spell off.  <BR>
One last thing before moving on to killing the Gnome, be warned while going for a capture that the Gnomes have many allies.  They are often seen travelling with Dwarves and Halflings.  And while Halflings are little retards who can't do anything, they WILL be able to take all of your platinum in the wink of an eye!  <BR>
OK, so now you have yourself a Gnome, using one of the above mentioned methods or one of your own (not recomended).  What do you do with him?  Why kill it of course!  However, this shouldn't be taken lightly!  Though Gnomes are physicaly weaker than the rest of the species of Norrath (yes, even more so than the infamous Giant Rat), they are kniving little bastards with more than a few tricks up your sleeve.  <BR>
I will first be looking at killing the Gnome from a warriors perspective, or other primarily melee type (Monk, Ranger, Paladin, Rogue, etc.).  OK, the one advantage you have is that no matter what profession the gnome is (Mage or Fighter), you will always be stronger than him.  So if you come against another Gnome meleer, its pretty damn easy.  However, if you come against a Gnomish caster (Necromancer, Enchanter, Magician, or Wizard are the most common), then it may be a bit more difficult.  The first thing to remember is to NOT be nervous.  They can smell fear and anxiety and strive off of it!  Just stay calm and confident.  Next, make sure that you have several items on you that protect you from magic, or higher your resistance to it.  This will help alot.  And last, try to attack as fast as possible in hopes of disrupting the Gnomes spellcasting.  If all goes well, you'll have yourself one dead Gnome!  Good luck!<BR>
Next is attacking a gnome from a Priests perspective (Cleric, Druid, Shaman).  I don't suggest going in alone against a Gnome as one of these classes...  HOWEVER, if you gather one or two more of your friends (any class), with you they can be the most effective Gnome-killing machinese in all Norrath.  Just play is as if you were fighting a mob, buff and heal your comrades as they deal out damage to the wee one, and every now and then shock the little runt with a spell, and everything should be fine.  The Monk and Cleric VS Gnome is one of my most favorite combinations.  If you must attack it alone, buff yourself as much as possible and stick to rooting the Gnome.  <BR>
Then we have taking down a Gnome from the casters perspective: beating the Gnome at its own game.  This can be a difficult battle unless you are very skilled.  Fortunately you will go up against a Gnomish Warrior or other melee class.  This will give you the advantage because you can cimply root the thing and then assault it with an onslaught of spells.  If you have a pet or other summoned minion, it will be even easier!  Just stay calm and try to be in control the whole fight.  If things go wrong, don't be afraid to run for help; just hope you don't run into more MIDGETS!  If fate is against you, however, you will go up against another Gnomish caster.  In this battle, Gnomes most always have the advantage unless you are a Dark Elf or High Elf, for Gnomes are naturally more intelligent than most other races, thus highering their spellcasting abilities.  There is not much advice I can give here but put all of your skill into the battle; hopefully you will be with friends.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
PART IV: QUICK TIPS<BR>
<BR>
-Always hunt and kill gnomes with friends.  It makes it SO much easier, and it is a great experience!<BR>
-BEWARE: Gnomes are known to travel in packs with each other, or Dwarves and Halflings.  You may have to retreat if outnumbered.<BR>
-They may only be up to your knees, but they can pack quite a punch.  Spellcasters and Priests: don't be deceived by the Gnome warriors size, always be alert.<BR>
-Gnomes are gay.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
EPILOGUE:<BR>
<BR>
So there you have it folks, The Complete Guide to Killing Gnomes.  I hope you enoyed reading it as much as I enjoyed writing it.  I hope it helps, good luck.<BR>
<BR>
LOOK FOR A COMPLETE GUIDE TO KILLING ELVES, COMING SOON!<BR>
<BR>
                   -Kaiyan.<BR>

